            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How the HECS-HELP repayment calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool models the Australian
                <strong>Higher Education Loan Program (HELP)</strong>, including
                HECS-HELP, to estimate your
                <strong>compulsory repayment</strong> and how
                <strong>indexation</strong> affects your debt over time. It is
                designed as an educational guide and planning aid – it does not
                replace official ATO calculations.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Compulsory repayment formula</h3>
              <p>
                Each financial year, if your
                <strong>repayment income</strong> is above the minimum
                threshold, you must make a compulsory repayment. The ATO applies
                a <strong>repayment rate</strong> to your entire repayment
                income:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="mb-1">
                  <strong>Repayment income</strong> ≈ taxable income +
                  reportable fringe benefits + some super contributions + other
                  adjustments
                </p>
                <p class="mb-1">
                  <strong>Compulsory repayment</strong> = repayment income ×
                  repayment rate
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                For example, if your repayment income is
                <code>$80,000</code> and the applicable rate is <code>5%</code>:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  Compulsory repayment = 0.05 × 80,000 = <strong>$4,000</strong>
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Indexation (CPI) on 1 June</h3>
              <p>
                HELP debts are <strong>indexed to inflation</strong> each year
                on <strong>1 June</strong>. Indexation is applied to the
                <em>remaining balance</em> after your compulsory and voluntary
                repayments for the year have been credited.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="mb-1">
                  <strong>Indexed balance</strong> = remaining balance × (1 +
                  indexation rate)
                </p>
                <p class="mb-1">
                  Indexation amount = remaining balance × indexation rate
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator lets you choose an indexation rate (for example,
                4%) so you can see how different inflation scenarios change your
                long‑term costs.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Order of calculations in this tool</h3>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Determine your repayment bracket and rate from the threshold
                  table.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Calculate compulsory repayment = repayment income × rate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Apply compulsory repayment and any voluntary repayment to
                  reduce your balance.
                </li>
                <li>Apply indexation to the remaining balance.</li>
                <li>
                  Repeat for future years (assuming constant income and
                  indexation) to estimate time to clear the debt.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Worked example</h2>
              <p>Suppose:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Repayment income: <strong>$80,000</strong></li>
                <li>Current HECS-HELP balance: <strong>$30,000</strong></li>
                <li>Repayment rate at this income: <strong>5%</strong></li>
                <li>Indexation rate: <strong>4%</strong></li>
                <li>Voluntary repayment: <strong>$1,000</strong></li>
              </ul>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Compulsory repayment = 0.05 × 80,000 =
                  <strong>$4,000</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Total repayment this year = 4,000 + 1,000 =
                  <strong>$5,000</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Balance after repayments = 30,000 − 5,000 =
                  <strong>$25,000</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Indexation amount = 25,000 × 0.04 = <strong>$1,000</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  End‑of‑year balance = 25,000 + 1,000 =
                  <strong>$26,000</strong>.
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                Even though you repaid $5,000, indexation added $1,000 back, so
                your net reduction in debt was $4,000. This is why many
                graduates choose to make voluntary repayments before 1 June when
                they can afford it.
              </p>

              <h2>Tips for managing your HECS-HELP debt</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Check your income estimate</strong> – use your latest
                  payslips or last year’s tax return as a guide.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Update thresholds annually</strong> – the ATO
                  publishes new thresholds and rates each year.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Consider voluntary repayments before 1 June</strong>
                  if you want to reduce indexation.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Tell your employer you have a HELP debt</strong> so
                  they can withhold extra tax and avoid a bill at tax time.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Review your plan if your income changes</strong>
                  (promotion, part‑time work, parental leave, moving overseas).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations & disclaimer</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator is a simplified model based on public
                information about the Australian HELP system. It does
                <strong>not</strong> account for every possible adjustment (such
                as foreign income reporting rules, multiple loan types, or
                mid‑year changes in income).
              </p>
              <p>
                For binding calculations and personalised advice, always refer
                to the
                <a
                  href="https://www.ato.gov.au"
                  target="_blank"
                  rel="noopener noreferrer"
                  >Australian Taxation Office (ATO)</a
                >,
                <a
                  href="https://www.studyassist.gov.au"
                  target="_blank"
                  rel="noopener noreferrer"
                  >StudyAssist</a
                >, or a qualified tax professional.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>
                Do I have to make repayments if my income is below the
                threshold?
              </h3>
              <p>
                No. If your repayment income is below the minimum threshold for
                the year, you do not have to make a compulsory repayment.
                However, your debt will still be indexed each year, so voluntary
                repayments can still reduce your long‑term cost.
              </p>

              <h3>Are HECS-HELP repayments tax-deductible?</h3>
              <p>
                Compulsory and voluntary HELP repayments are generally
                <strong>not tax-deductible</strong> for individuals. They are
                treated as repayments of a government loan, not as deductible
                expenses.
              </p>

              <h3>What happens to my HECS-HELP debt if I die?</h3>
              <p>
                Under current rules, any remaining HELP debt is
                <strong>written off</strong> when the ATO is notified of your
                death. It is not recovered from your estate or your family.
              </p>
